12 maintained by the employer. The bulletin may be included in any printed abstract
13 posted by the employer pursuant to NRS 608.013.
14 4. The provisions of this section shall not be construed to:
15 (a) Limit or abridge any other rights, remedies or procedures available under
16 the law;
17 (b) Negate any other rights, remedies or procedures available to an aggrieved
18 party;
19 (c) Prohibit, preempt or discourage any contract or other agreement that
20 provides a more generous sick leave benefit or paid time off benefit; or
21 (d) Extend the maximum amount of leave to which an employee is entitled to
22 take pursuant to the Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993, 29 U.S.C. §§ 2601 et
23 seq. ; or
24 (e) Diminish the obligation of an employer to comply with any of the
25 following that provide the same or a more generous sick leave [benefit or paid
26 time off] benefit:
27 (1) A collective bargaining agreement;
28 (2) A policy of the employer;
29 (3) An employment contract; or
30 (4) Any applicable local, state or federal law.
31 5. An employer shall not deny an employee the right to use accrued sick leave
32 in accordance with the provisions of this section or retaliate against an employee
33 for attempting to prosecute a violation of this section or for exercising any rights
34 afforded by this section.
35 6. The provisions of this section do not apply [:
36 (a) To] to the extent prohibited by federal law . [; or
37 (b) With regard to an employee of the employer if the employee is covered
38 under a valid collective bargaining agreement.]
39 7. As used in this section, “immediate family” means:
40 (a) The child, foster child, spouse, domestic partner, sibling, parent, mother-in-
41 law, father-in-law, grandchild, grandparent or stepparent of an employee; or
42 (b) Any person for whom the employee is the legal guardian.
